Task 1 Solving Fashion-MNIST with Convolutional Neural Networks¶

(weight ~20%)

In Assignment 1, you tackled the image classification problem in Fashion-MNIST. There, you used a Densely Connected Neural Network. You should now know that is not an optimal model architecture for the problem. In Assignment 2, you will apply the best practices of deep-learning computer vision to improve the image classification performance.

Task 1.1 Revisit Fashion-MNIST classification with DNN¶

(weight ~3%)

Review your Assignment 1 solution, and reproduce the experiment here. Try to improve the model without changing the model architecture.

den_test_images = den_test_images.astype('float32') / 255

#1-hot-coding for labels

den_test_labels = to_categorical(test_labels)

In [0]:
#Splitting training data into training and validation dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_val, Y_train, Y_val = train_test_split(den_train_images, den_train_labels, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 12345)

#Constructing tensorflow input pipeline
train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, Y_train))
train_dataset = train_dataset.shuffle(buffer_size=512, seed=14).batch(512)

test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((den_test_images, den_test_labels))
test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(512)

val_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_val, Y_val))
val_dataset = val_dataset.batch(512)
1.1.5 Model architecture¶
In [0]:
#Building architect of the network
def make_model():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu',input_shape=[28*28],kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.0001)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu',kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.0001)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  return model

model = make_model()  
model.summary()

1.1.6 Compiling and fitting the model¶
In [0]:
#Learning scheduler
def scheduler(epoch):
  if epoch < 5:
    return 0.001
  else:
    return 0.001 * tf.math.exp(0.1 * (5 - epoch))

callback = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(scheduler)

history = model.fit(train_dataset,
                    steps_per_epoch=steps,
                    epochs = 50,
                    validation_data=val_dataset,
                    validation_steps=val_steps,
                    callbacks = [callback])

In [0]:
#Base model accuracy on test dataset
model_eval = model.evaluate(den_test_images, den_test_labels)

313/313 [==============================] - 1s 2ms/step - loss: 0.3544 - accuracy: 0.8945

Previous base model was overfitting with optimizer RMSProp (lr = 0.001), two hidden layers including output layer with 256 units each. This model acheived accuracy of 0.8945 on test dataset. Since the model overfitted, multiple combination of dropout rate, learning rate scheduler, and regularlization (l2) was tried. Model with dropout rate 0.2, learning rate and regularization (l2) of 0.0001 provided more stable model. Also, echo steps were calculated using default formula (image count/batch size) and added to the model. After ~20 epochs this model starts overfitting.

Task 1.2 Train a ConvNet from scratch¶

(weight ~5%)

Build a ConvNet to replace the densely connected network in Task 1.1. Report the classification accuracy on the test set. Aim to achieve higher accuracy.

1.2.1 Preprocess images¶
In [0]:
#Reshaping and normalizing training and test images
con_train_images = train_images.reshape((-1, 28,28,1))
con_train_images = con_train_images.astype('float32')/255
con_test_images = test_images.reshape((-1,28,28,1))
con_test_images = con_test_images.astype('float32')/255

#Standardizing training and test images
con_train_images = (con_train_images-(con_train_images.mean()))/(con_train_images.std())
con_test_images = (con_test_images-(con_test_images.mean()))/(con_test_images.std())

#1-hot-coding for labels
con_train_labels = to_categorical(train_labels)
con_test_labels = to_categorical(test_labels)
In [0]:
#Splitting training data into training and validation dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train_con, X_val_con, Y_train_con, Y_val_con = train_test_split(con_train_images, con_train_labels, test_size = 0.1, random_state = 12000)

#Constructing tensorflow input pipeline
con_train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train_con, Y_train_con))
con_train_dataset = con_train_dataset.shuffle(buffer_size=512, seed=14).batch(512)

con_test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((con_test_images, con_test_labels))
con_test_dataset = con_test_dataset.batch(512)

con_val_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_val_con, Y_val_con))
con_val_dataset = con_val_dataset.batch(512)
1.2.2 Model architecture¶
In [0]:
def build_model():
  con_model = models.Sequential()
  con_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  data_format='channels_last', input_shape=(28,28,1)))
  con_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  con_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  data_format='channels_last'))
  con_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  con_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
  con_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  data_format='channels_last'))
  con_model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  con_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))    
  con_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  data_format='channels_last'))
  con_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  con_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
  con_model.add(layers.Flatten())
  con_model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
  con_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  con_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
  con_model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  con_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  con_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
  con_model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  return con_model

con_model = build_model()  
con_model.summary()

# Resize the images 56*56 as required by VGG16
from keras.preprocessing.image import img_to_array, array_to_img

X_train_da = np.asarray([img_to_array(array_to_img(im, scale=False).resize((56,56))) for im in X_train_da])
X_test_da = np.asarray([img_to_array(array_to_img(im, scale=False).resize((56,56))) for im in X_test_da])

      format(X_train_da.shape, X_test_da.shape))

In [0]:
from tensorflow.keras import models
from tensorflow.keras import layers
from tensorflow.keras import optimizers

def transfer_model():
  new_model = models.Sequential()
  new_model.add(conv_base)
  new_model.add(layers.Flatten())
  new_model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation = 'relu',kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.0001)))
  new_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  new_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.30))
  new_model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation = 'relu',kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.0001)))
  new_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  new_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.30))
  new_model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  return new_model

new_model = transfer_model()
new_model.summary()

In [0]:
def final_model():
  final_model = models.Sequential()
  final_model.add(conv_base)
  final_model.add(layers.Flatten())
  final_model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation = 'relu'))
  final_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  final_model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
  final_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  final_model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
  final_model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
  final_model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  return final_model

tuned_model = final_model()
tuned_model.summary()

Task 1.4 Performance comparison¶

(weight ~2%)

Record the test accuracy achieved at different training configurations above. Which method achieved the highest accuracy? Why did it work better for this problem?

Convolution model in Task 1.2 was best among the four models. It has lowest test loss and computational time whilst highest test accuracy. This model converges in 20 epochs after which it starts overfitting. Possible reason are;

1) Increase in layers/size of the model might reduce accuracy and increase error rate (degradation problem). 2) VGG16 pre-trained weights are trained on image size of 224x224 wit RGB channel. Although, it can accept minimum 32x32 image size. But I guess, this model should work better on original color images instead of converted color images (conversion from 1 channel to 3 channels). 3) Due to increase in image size and channels, we need to add more layers which makes model time inefficient if its trained on CPU (less RAM). 4) VGG16 architecutre is too huge for fashion-mnist kind of data whcih results in overfitting. 5) I guess, data augmentation should work better on color images of living things instead of stalled things.

#Preprocessing images
CIFAR_train_images = CIFAR_train_images.astype('float32')/255
CIFAR_test_images = CIFAR_test_images.astype('float32')/255

#Standardizing training and test images
CIFAR_train_images = (CIFAR_train_images-(CIFAR_train_images.mean()))/(CIFAR_train_images.std())
CIFAR_test_images = (CIFAR_test_images-(CIFAR_test_images.mean()))/(CIFAR_test_images.std())

#1-hot-coding for labels
CIFAR_train_label = to_categorical(CIFAR_train_labels)
CIFAR_test_label = to_categorical(CIFAR_test_labels)

#Creating gGenerators
training_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()
validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()
testing_datagen = ImageDataGenerator()
batches_size = 64

train_batches = len(X_train_CIFAR) // batches_size
val_batches = len(X_val_CIFAR) // batches_size
test_batches = len(CIFAR_test_images) // batches_size


training_generator = training_datagen.flow(X_train_CIFAR, Y_train_CIFAR, 
                                         batch_size=batches_size,
                                         shuffle=True)
validation_generator = validation_datagen.flow(X_val_CIFAR, Y_val_CIFAR, 
                                         batch_size=batches_size)
testing_generator = testing_datagen.flow(CIFAR_test_images, CIFAR_test_label,
                                       batch_size=batches_size)
In [0]:
#Model architecture
def base_model():
  cifar_base_model = models.Sequential()
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  kernel_initializer='he_uniform', input_shape=(32,32,3)))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', strides=1, padding='same', 
                  kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Flatten())
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu',kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.0001)))
  cifar_base_model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  return cifar_base_model

cifar_base_model = base_model()  
cifar_base_model.summary()

Task 2.1.3 Train a ResNet¶

Train a residual neural network (ResNet) on the CIFAR10 training data and report the test accuracy and the training time.

The ResNet is a popular network architecture for image classification. You may find more information about how ResNet works by reading this paper.

(You may implement a resnet model or use an existing implementation. In either case, you should not use pretrained network weights.)

resnet_test_labels = to_categorical(CIFAR_test_labels,num_classes)

# Subtracting pixel mean improves accuracy

# If subtract pixel mean is enabled
if subtract_pixel_mean:
    resnet_train_images_mean = np.mean(resnet_train_images, axis=0)
    resnet_train_images -= resnet_train_images_mean
    resnet_test_images -= resnet_train_images_mean

In [0]:
#From keras.io
def lr_schedule(epoch):
    lr = 1e-3
    if epoch > 180:
        lr *= 0.5e-3
    elif epoch > 160:
        lr *= 1e-3
    elif epoch > 120:
        lr *= 1e-2
    elif epoch > 80:
        lr *= 1e-1
    return lr

lr_scheduler = LearningRateScheduler(lr_schedule)

lr_reducer = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_loss',
    factor=np.sqrt(0.1),
    patience=5,
    verbose=1,
    mode='auto',
    min_delta=0.0001,
    cooldown=0,
    min_lr=0.5e-6)


res_callback = [lr_reducer, lr_scheduler]
In [0]:
def resnet_layer(inputs,
                 num_filters=16,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 strides=1,
                 activation='relu',
                 batch_normalization=True,
                 conv_first=True):
    
    conv = Conv2D(num_filters,
                  kernel_size=kernel_size,
                  strides=strides,
                  padding='same',
                  kernel_initializer='he_normal',
                  kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4))

    x = inputs
    if conv_first:
        x = conv(x)
        if batch_normalization:
            x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        if activation is not None:
            x = Activation(activation)(x)
    else:
        if batch_normalization:
            x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        if activation is not None:
            x = Activation(activation)(x)
        x = conv(x)
    return x
In [0]:
def resnet_v1(input_shape, depth, num_classes=10):
  
    
    # Start model definition.
    num_filters = 16
    num_res_blocks = int((depth - 2) / 6)

    inputs = Input(shape=input_shape)
    x = resnet_layer(inputs=inputs)
    # Instantiate the stack of residual units
    for stack in range(3):
        for res_block in range(num_res_blocks):
            strides = 1
            if stack > 0 and res_block == 0:  # first layer but not first stack
                strides = 2  # downsample
            y = resnet_layer(inputs=x,
                             num_filters=num_filters,
                             strides=strides)
            y = resnet_layer(inputs=y,
                             num_filters=num_filters,
                             activation=None)
            if stack > 0 and res_block == 0:  # first layer but not first stack
                # linear projection residual shortcut connection to match
                # changed dims
                x = resnet_layer(inputs=x,
                                 num_filters=num_filters,
                                 kernel_size=1,
                                 strides=strides,
                                 activation=None,
                                 batch_normalization=False)
            x = keras.layers.add([x, y])
            x = Activation('relu')(x)
        num_filters *= 2

    # Add classifier on top.
    # v1 does not use BN after last shortcut connection-ReLU
    x = AveragePooling2D(pool_size=8)(x)
    y = Flatten()(x)
    outputs = Dense(num_classes,
                    activation='softmax',
                    kernel_initializer='he_normal')(y)

    # Instantiate model.
    model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
    return model

Since data augmentation provided better test accuracy and less overfit than without augmentation, Task 2.2 will be done on augmented data.

Task 2.2 Fast training of ResNet¶

(weight ~10%)

In this task, you will experiment with different ways to reduce the time for training your ResNet on CIFAR10. There are different ways to speed up neural network training; below are two ideas. Please select at least one idea to implement. Explain the experiment steps and report the final performance and training time.

Option 1. Learning rate schedule¶

Use a learning rate schedule for the training. Some popular learning rate schedules include

  • the Step Decay learning rate (e.g., see here)
  • Cyclical learning rates
  • The exponential learning rate

Also Keras provides some convenient functions that you can use.

Option 2. Look ahead optimiser¶

Read this paper and implement the Lookahead optimiser.

Option 1 - Learning rate schedule

2.2.1.1 Step Decay learning rate

#From Towards data science
def step_decay(epoch):
   initial_lrate = 0.001
   drop = 0.5
   epochs_drop = 5.0
   lrate = initial_lrate*tf.math.pow(drop,  
           tf.math.floor((1+epoch)/epochs_drop))
   return float(lrate)

lr_decay=LearningRateScheduler(step_decay)

res_callback = [lr_decay]

%%time

res_model_lr_decay.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(lr = 0.001, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

history_res_model_lr_decay = res_model_lr_decay.fit_generator(
    res_training_generator,
    steps_per_epoch=res_train_batches,
    epochs=50,
    validation_data=res_validation_generator,
    validation_steps=res_val_batches,
    callbacks = res_callback)

 Test Loss: 0.38

Step decay takes three hyperparameters, drop parameter defines percentage drop in lr, epochs_drop defines interval of epochs for such drop, and lastly intial lr. Setting drop to 0.5 constant, model was fine tuned using intial rate to 0.001 and epoch_drop to 5. To tal number of epochs i.e. 50 and general trial performance was considered to set these hyperparametes.

2.2.1.2 Cyclical learning rate

In [0]:
#From kaggle
from keras.callbacks import Callback
class CyclicLR(Callback):
    def __init__(
            self,base_lr=0.0001,
            max_lr=0.0006,step_size=2000.,
            mode='triangular',gamma=1.,
            scale_fn=None,scale_mode='cycle'):
        
        super(CyclicLR, self).__init__()

        if mode not in ['triangular', 'triangular2','exp_range']:
            raise KeyError("mode must be one of 'triangular', "
                           "'triangular2', or 'exp_range'")
        self.base_lr = base_lr
        self.max_lr = max_lr
        self.step_size = step_size
        self.mode = mode
        self.gamma = gamma
        if scale_fn is None:
            if self.mode == 'triangular':
                self.scale_fn = lambda x: 1.
                self.scale_mode = 'cycle'
            elif self.mode == 'triangular2':
                self.scale_fn = lambda x: 1 / (2.**(x - 1))
                self.scale_mode = 'cycle'
            elif self.mode == 'exp_range':
                self.scale_fn = lambda x: gamma ** x
                self.scale_mode = 'iterations'
        else:
            self.scale_fn = scale_fn
            self.scale_mode = scale_mode
        self.clr_iterations = 0.
        self.trn_iterations = 0.
        self.history = {}

        self._reset()

    def _reset(self, new_base_lr=None, new_max_lr=None,
               new_step_size=None):
        if new_base_lr is not None:
            self.base_lr = new_base_lr
        if new_max_lr is not None:
            self.max_lr = new_max_lr
        if new_step_size is not None:
            self.step_size = new_step_size
        self.clr_iterations = 0.
        
    def clr(self):
        cycle = np.floor(1 + self.clr_iterations / (2 * self.step_size))
        x = np.abs(self.clr_iterations / self.step_size - 2 * cycle + 1)
        if self.scale_mode == 'cycle':
            return self.base_lr + (self.max_lr - self.base_lr) * \
                np.maximum(0, (1 - x)) * self.scale_fn(cycle)
        else:
            return self.base_lr + (self.max_lr - self.base_lr) * \
                np.maximum(0, (1 - x)) * self.scale_fn(self.clr_iterations)

    def on_train_begin(self, logs={}):
        logs = logs or {}

        if self.clr_iterations == 0:
            K.set_value(self.model.optimizer.lr, self.base_lr)
        else:
            K.set_value(self.model.optimizer.lr, self.clr())

    def on_batch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):

        logs = logs or {}
        self.trn_iterations += 1
        self.clr_iterations += 1
        K.set_value(self.model.optimizer.lr, self.clr())

        self.history.setdefault(
            'lr', []).append(
            K.get_value(
                self.model.optimizer.lr))
        self.history.setdefault('iterations', []).append(self.trn_iterations)

        for k, v in logs.items():
            self.history.setdefault(k, []).append(v)

    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        logs = logs or {}
        logs['lr'] = K.get_value(self.model.optimizer.lr)

313/313 [==============================] - 10s 33ms/step
Test accuracy: 0.79
 Test Loss: 1.51

Cyclical learning rate (lr) schedules lr that monotonically decreases after each epoch. It allows model to descend into lower areas of the landscape instead of converging early. Class code was taken from kaggle which has hyperparameters like minimum lr, maximum lr which gives boundary to the lr, step_size defines the cycle. There are various variants available like, triangle (same range of lr), triangle2 (range of lr reduces) which is simiilar to expo_range variant. Due to time constraint, only triangular mode (variant) was tried and tested. Cycles in loss and accuracy for training and validation is evident from above graphs.

2.2.1.3 Exponential decay learning rate

In [0]:
#Defining exponential decay (towardsdatascience.com)
def exp_decay(epoch):
   intial_lr = 0.001
   d = 0.1
   lr = intial_lr*np.exp(-d*epoch)
   return lr

exp_decay=LearningRateScheduler(exp_decay)

res_callback = [exp_decay]

Exponential decay has the mathematical form of lr=intial_lr exp(-kepoch). Initial learning rate hyperparameter is used based on knowledge gained from previous models, k and epochs defines the steps for exponential.

Task 2.3 Performance comparison¶

(weight ~3%)

Based on the above experiments, which method or which combination of methods result in the best accuracy with the same training time.

Due to time constraint and constantly running out of GPU, I could run only 50 epochs for steps decay lr and 30 epochs for expoential decay. However, steps decay model got converged after 30 epochs based on training loss/accuracy. Thus, it is still considered comparable with other models with 100 epochs. Best model is with steps decay which provided 0.38 loss and 0.86 accuracy on test data. Also, it was comparatively time efficient. Base model is quick, but it suffers from severe overfit and validation loss shoots up after 20 epochs. As mentioned earlier, data augmentation provided better fit on original RGB image rather than converted RGB image as we did for VGG16 fashion-mnist. Step decay performs well may because gradient descent of loss takes bigger steps earlier towards minima and takes smaller steps once near minima. This helps model to find more deeper loss space. Cyclic lr also performs better, but due to its cyclic nature, it impacts test loss tends to be higher. However, other variants of decaying cyclic rates are worth trying. My favorite hyperparameter is learning rate, because it gives me indirect access to adjust the gradient which affects the weights and accuracy. Also, I would like to understand why sometimes loss and accuracy move is same direction whereas logically it should inverse relationship. I have observed that while evaluating model on test data, test loss is different for test data given in mini batches and entire test dataset. Please suggest which method is technically and ethically correct. I have kept test data in batches to be in consistent with training and validation data.
